callforspeaker.content:
DevFest Calgary is bringing over 100 developers together **November 3** together in Calgary in the beautiful Riddel Library at MRU. Our focus is the content. **We’re looking for speakers like you**, who are ready to rock the stage and deliver the best talk or workshop in the field.
Submit a proposal

Why is it cool to speak at the DevFest?
DevFest Calgary is not an ordinary tech conference, besides selecting only the best speakers, we help them to succeed in delivering an exceptional quality talk on the stage. Here are few perks that all our speakers get:
**Exposure**. By being a speaker, you are proving your level of expertise to a potential business partners or employers. Your talk will be promoted in our online resources and recording published in YouTube channel.
**Unique networking**. Being a speaker means you’ll have the unique chance to network with other speakers - the best experts in the industry.
**Coaching**. We're in the same boat, after being selected as a speaker our program committee will help you to deliver the best talk possible. We provide information about the audience, presentation templates, feedback on the slides, all to help you to prepare.
What are we looking for? We're looking for **experience-based talks**, the information that can not be found in the documentation or easily googled. We're looking for your stories, your struggles, research results and experiences with the frontier tools or technologies. Check the [list of topics](https://codelabs.developers.google.com/devfest18) we're interested in (it is not full and updated all the time). You can submit as many talks as you want. This year we accept submissions in two formats:
- 45 minutes sessions
- 10 Minute Lightning Talks
- 1-2 hour workshops

Talks that will not pass initial review:
- Talks about a specific tool/library/project explaining how it works or how to use it.
- Talks whose focus is pitching a company or project. It’s cool that you mention your company during the presentation, but it shouldn’t be the focus of the talk.
- Proposals that are not in English.
- Recruitment talks to attract talent.

We strongly recommend you check out [speaking.io](http://speaking.io) website from Zach Holman. It includes good tips and guidelines for speakers.
Timeline ** Call for Papers submission deadline is October 15, 2018**. Submission results will be announced by October 20. Any questions? Email organizers at speakers@gdgyyc.com
Submit a proposal
callforspeaker.title: We're looking for speakers

dfca18-announced.brief: It is official. DevFestYYC 2019 will take place in Calgary, November 22-23.
dfca18-announced.content:
It is official. DevFestYYC 2019 will take place in **Calgary, on November 22-23**. Described as "Where Alberta's future is launching!", DevFestYYC 2019 is bringing world-class Google Cloud and Cloud Native experts to Calgary. Building on the success of DevFestYYC 2018, we've grown from a small 100-people event to the biggest Google technology celebration in Western Canada. This year, we expect over 330+ developers, data scientists, cloud architects, technologists and entrepreneurs from around the world to join us to learn about about cutting edge Android, Web and Google Cloud technologies. We combine this incredible learning opportunity with a phenomenal atmosphere and the gorgeous Calgary Central Libray, and DevFestYYC is sure to be unforgettable!

What to expect? **4 parallel Tracks: Learn about Cloud Infrastructure, Data & Analytics, Code and Development and Developer programs.** You will hear and learn from speakers and presenters from leading companies like Google, SoftServe, Flexera, ATB and AIRIA.

We are stoked to see yo all there!
Register

DevFestYYC 2019 Team.
dfca18-announced.title: Announcing DevFestYYC 2019

Large scale enterprise migrations are challenging. With billions of connections and thousands of dependencies creating extreme complexity, migrations are one of the most difficult projects to execute successfully. 

How do you launch your migration successfully?

From discovery and application dependency identification through to Migration, in 45 minutes we'll cover how DATA can fuel your understanding, power optimization, and accelerate modernization and help you successfully navigate your cloud migration.

139725.description:
Cloud Functions for Firebase empowers web, mobile, and IoT developers to build simple, yet powerful backend features to their applications. I will be covering a quick intro into the what & why of Cloud Functions and finish up with some typical use-cases & examples of Cloud Functions for Firebase.

Have you ever started building an application and quickly realized that a lot of back-end work is needed? Cloud Functions is a serverless execution environment for building and connecting cloud services. With Cloud Functions you write simple, single-purpose functions that are attached to events emitted from your cloud infrastructure and services. There is no need to provision any infrastructure or worry about managing any servers.

In this session, you’ll see how using Cloud Functions for Firebase can help you quickly build out task heavy features for your web/mobile/IoT application as well as easily integrate with 3rd-party tools & services.
139725.title: Supercharging your applications with Cloud Functions

153631.description:
Flutter is taking the world by storm, enabling developers to write 90%+ of an app just once, then reuse that code to release to mobile, desktop and web.

Join us for Flutter 102, Layout Basics! Together we'll work through a customized workshop that was inspired by a layout tutorial designed by the Flutter team itself. When we're done, you know how easy it is to put together a great UI in Flutter!

So come get some hands-on experience with Flutter, and see how it can make your life a whole lot easier!

Please have Flutter installed and test that you can create a basic Flutter app before this workshop. We don't have enough time to walk people through installing Flutter and do the workshop too.
153631.title: Get hands on with Flutter! Flutter 102, Layout Basics

146605.description:
Artificial intelligence and machine learning (AI and ML) are major buzzwords right now. But as much as people are talking about AI, what does it actually mean for business? In ML 101, we'll answer this and more, including:

What exactly is AI/ML and why is it happening now?

Why is there an opportunity here in Alberta?

Where has AI/ML been applied successfully in industry?

And, most importantly: how can a company embark on an AI/ML strategy?

This will be a tech-free presentation. No jargon, just a basic look at artificial intelligence, machine learning and what they can do for business.
146605.title: Machine Learning 101

139721.description:
The web is advancing at an alarming rate and browsers are providing new features giving web developers the ability to features to engage with mobile users. Using PWAs, web developers can provide “app like” experiences for their web apps without the need for a native (or hybrid) app.

As developers, we want to create apps that engage users across multiple devices. But building native apps is costly and cumbersome. Progressive Web Apps (PWAs) are experiences that combine the best of the web and the best of mobile apps using new web standards, including service workers, push notifications, and homescreen access.

In this session, you’ll learn the the fundamentals needed for building Progressive Web Apps, including the app shell model, how to use service workers to cache the App Shell and your key application data and more!
139721.title: What are Progressive Web Apps and How do they work?

148133.description:

142551.description: Build what’s next together - whether you are a developer or not. Google Cloud has given business users and knowledge workers to build enterprise custom applications to simplify processes and solve business problems. G-Suite in particular has enabled these “non-coders” to build powerful solutions in Sheets, Forms and App Maker. In this session, I will cover how easy it is to develop using G-Suite, how to integrate with Google Cloud Platform technologies such as AutoML, and how coders and non-coders can work together to develop solutions quicker and better.
142551.title: Empowering Business Users & Knowledge Workers with Google Cloud

139722.description:
Voice is quickly becoming the new standard for search and most businesses are not ready for it. Using Actions on Google, developers are able to design, build, and distribute fully-customizable conversational applications.

Actions on Google is a developer platform that lets you create software to extend the functionality of the Google Assistant, Google’s virtual personal assistant, across more than 500 million devices, including smart speakers, phones, cars, TVs, headphones, watches, and much more.

In this session, you’ll learn the fundamentals needed for building Actions on Google, including Voice UI (VUI) & conversational design, what tools are available, some resources to get you started, and more!
139722.title: Actions on Google: Are you prepared for the next type of search?

148188.description: At Quizlet, one of our highest throughput services, backed by MySQL, has been the source of multiple performance problems. In addition to the high throughput, the data managed by this service has a growth rate of ~2 billion records/month (and increasing!). At peak traffic, the service takes upwards of 10K writes/second. With scalability problems breathing down our neck, we decided to migrate our data and workload on to Cloud Spanner. There were challenges at every step of the way, from designing the schema, to migrating data, and getting a microservice serving from Cloud Spanner, without taking an outage. Did we succeed? What lessons did we learn along the way? Come find out.
148188.title: Keeping it Re(lation)al: moving from MySQL to Cloud Spanner without skipping a beat

138512.description:
As of v1.8.2 the Flutter team strongly recommends using Provider for all state management solutions, large or small. This is straight from the horse's mouth, Chris Sells, Program Manager for Flutter.

Interestingly enough, the Flutter team released a package called "Package Provider" three days after Remi Rousselet released his package, "Provider". During the time each of these was developed, Remi had no idea the team was working on a solution and neither did the team know about Remi. But here's the twist in the plot...

When the team looked at both packages, they recommended Remi's version over their own. They so strongly recommend it that they announced to the world at Google I/O19 that Remi's is better, and people should use it.

Come find out why.
138512.title: Flutter: State Management with Provider

147581.description:
New to microservices within the Enterprise? Come learn some of the core concepts around Microservices and how to start to decouple away from your Enterprise monolithic application.

Core concepts of Enterprise Microservices include Designing Microservices, Service Communications, Data Management, Governance, Integrating Microservices  and the Service Mesh.

139724.description:
Have you ever started building an application and quickly realized that a lot of back-end work is needed? Firebase is a platform that helps you quickly develop real-time apps, grow your user base, and earn more money. Firebase is made up of complementary features that you can mix-and-match to fit your needs without needing to know anything about servers! In this session, you’ll see how using Firebase can help you quickly build out a real-time database with an authentication system that perfectly blends into a web application. With Firebase, we can build a complete application in half the time without any server side code involved.

Firebase is many things and this talk will explore the tools available that it provides. I will cover a quick intro of all tools available, deeper dive into the Firebase real-time database & authentication setup, and finish up with a quick multiplayer quiz (built on Firebase).
139724.title: Serverless Applications with Firebase

142401.description: A sharing of my adventure in using Google App Maker to develop a complex workflow tool while starting out with no previous web app development experience

148196.title: Using GCP managed services to deploy your webapp

148187.description: Google's Women Techmakers program provides visibility, community, and resources for women in technology. Learn more about what the initiatives are, what WTM can provide, and how you can get involved.

Tim_Chan.name: Tim Chan
Tim_Chan.bio:
Tim Chan has over 15 years of experience in the energy industry with a focus on integrated (upstream to downstream) energy, power generation, commodities trading and enterprise risk management.

He currently leads internal audit projects at Suncor Energy Inc., while previously leading teams of accountants in support of Suncor's supply and trading activities. He has also instructed at the University of Calgary, through the Haskayne School of Business, in the area of Financial Accounting.

In 2018, Tim helped to found Untapped Energy, a data science startup for data practitioners in the energy industry, in the Calgary area, organizing a weekend long datathon aim at solving problems for this industry.
Tim_Chan.title: Co-founder of Untapped Energy

Xueming_Zhao.name: Xueming Zhao
Xueming_Zhao.bio: Xueming grew up in Edmonton and joined ATB in 2005 as a Treasury Modeling Analyst. In 2011, she took an opportunity with a software company as a consultant for treasury and risk system implementation for banks in the US and China. She rejoined ATB in 2013 in treasury and is currently in the role of Managing Director, Balance Sheet Management. With the support of her team, she manages funds transfer pricing, interest rate risk, and net interest margin. Currently, she is attending the Executive MBA program at Oxford Said Business School.
Xueming_Zhao.shortBio: ATB Financial, Managing Director, Balance Sheet Management, Treasury
Xueming_Zhao.title: ATB Financial, Managing Director, Balance Sheet Management, Treasury

Stephen_King.bio: Stephen is the CEO of CMO4Hire, a digital brand marketing firm for B2B companies that drives triple-digit growth and reduces go-to-market complexity. He is also the Chairman and a co-Founder of A100 (www.thea100.org), an organization which aims to inspire and support generations of Alberta tech entrepreneurs. With a computer science degree and 30+ year career in software development & commercialization, Stephen has written over a million lines of code and sold more than $500M in software. He's been a startup founder and a CMO &  Director for large international firms. More information about his company and unique MarTech software solution can be found here: https://www.cmo4hire.com/  and  https://www.dbmms.io/. Stephen's also an accomplished guitarist and musician (https://www.reverbnation.com/stephenking)  Connect with him at https://www.linkedin.com/in/stephenking13/

Liam_Goguen.bio: I have been with CMO4Hire since May 2017. Within my role as the data scientist at the company, I have worked to optimize certain processes we use to serve clients and helped develop our data tracking, reporting and forecasting infrastructure, DBMMS.io, CMO4Hire's agile marketing platform. Previously, I worked approximately six years in financial advisory and equity research roles in Calgary. My skillset includes data trend analysis/forecasting, financial modeling/analysis/valuations, industry/company research, database creation/maintenance/optimization, analyzing financing proposals and key commercial agreements and financial due diligence. I have a Bachelor of Business Administration degree with a concentration in Finance from the Williams School of Business at Bishop's University, Quebec.
